As the Cephis- sus is out of the question here, Mr. Ellis supposes that Propertius followed some other legend, which connected the drowning of Argynnus with some point on the coast of Asia Minor. Ont oi severat names which might be connected with Argynnus, he selects ,the promontory Argennum, exactly opposite to the island of Chios, and conjectures Mimantis for minantis, showing that in MSS. Mimas has frequently been corrupted into minas, minax, and similar forms. Mount ammas is one of the three mountainous projections into which the peninsula between Teos (S.) and Clazomenae (N.) spreads γ itself out. Mr. Ellis points out that Agamemnon was specially honoured near Clazomenae (Pars. 7, 5. 6); and there were probably Agamemnon legends all along the Ionian coast. Assumiug therefore that ‘the waters of Mimas' might be used to denote a point on the shore near to the promontory of Argennum, he proposes to read either (a) Qum natat Argynni poena, Mimantis aquae, making aquae in apposition to litora, and translating ‘ Shores sig· nalised by the punishment of Argynnus, the waters of Mimas which drowned him :’ or else (b) Qua natat Argynni poena Mimantis aquas.

He prefers the former reading, as involving a slighter change, and as being more recondite. The authority of Mr. Ellis will doubt- less commend this reading to future editors: but I venture, with much diffidence, to think that there arc strong reasons against it. For (1) there is no legend that Argynnus was punishaa’ for anything. (a) The ‘waters of Mimas’ is a somewhat strange expressiori to denote a point on the shore near Mount Mimas. It was on a spur' of Mount Corycus, forming the Westem spur of the three· pronged peninsula, while Mimas was the Northem. The passage quoted by R. Ellis from Strabo gives Mimas its true position, be- tween Erythrae and Hypocremnns.
